          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which layer of bone is responsible for the intense pain experienced during a fra</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which layer of bone is responsible for the intense pain experienced during a fracture?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Endosteum</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The endosteum lines inner bone surfaces and contains osteoblasts/osteoclasts, but it is not densely innervated with pain fibres.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Compact bone</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Compact bone carries vasomotor fibres for blood flow regulation, but it is not the primary source of fracture pain.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Periosteum</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The periosteum is densely supplied with sensory nerve fibres, making it the primary source of acute fracture pain.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Spongy bone</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Spongy bone contains marrow and has some sensory fibres (causing deep aching in metastases), but the intense localised pain of fractures arises from the periosteum.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Review the four layers of bone. The periosteum is the outermost fibrous covering and is densely innervated — this is why fractures hurt so intensely."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done! The periosteum's rich nerve supply explains why fractures and periostitis cause such sharp, localised pain."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
