          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>The pubic symphysis and intervertebral discs are classified as secondary cartila</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>The pubic symphysis and intervertebral discs are classified as secondary cartilaginous joints (symphyses). What type of cartilage holds these joints together?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Hyaline cartilage</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Hyaline cartilage is found in primary cartilaginous joints (synchondroses), such as epiphyseal plates. Symphyses use a tougher material.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Elastic cartilage</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Elastic cartilage is found in the pinna, epiglottis, and auditory tube — not in weight-bearing joints like symphyses.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Fibrocartilage</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Symphyses use fibrocartilage, the heavy-duty type with thick type I collagen bundles, suited to the high mechanical loads at the pubic symphysis and between vertebral bodies.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>A combination of all three cartilage types</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Symphyses specifically use fibrocartilage. Each cartilage type has distinct locations — they do not combine within a single joint.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Secondary cartilaginous joints (symphyses) use fibrocartilage — the heavy-duty type with thick type I collagen bundles. Primary cartilaginous joints (synchondroses) use hyaline cartilage."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done! Fibrocartilage appears wherever mechanical loads are highest — intervertebral discs, pubic symphysis, knee menisci, and the labrum."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
