          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>A 7-year-old boy presents with unexplained medial knee pain but no knee patholog</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A 7-year-old boy presents with unexplained medial knee pain but no knee pathology on examination. Applying Hilton's law, which nerve pathway explains why hip disease can produce pain at the knee?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Femoral nerve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The femoral nerve supplies the hip joint and anterior thigh muscles, but its cutaneous territory is the anterior thigh and medial leg (via the saphenous branch) — not specifically the medial knee in this referral pattern.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Sciatic nerve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The sciatic nerve supplies the posterior thigh and leg. Hip pathology referred via the sciatic would produce posterior thigh or leg pain, not medial knee pain.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Obturator nerve</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The obturator nerve supplies the hip joint, adductor muscles, and skin over the medial knee. By Hilton's law, hip inflammation travels along this shared pathway and is felt at the medial knee.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Tibial nerve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The tibial nerve is a branch of the sciatic and supplies structures below the knee. It does not explain referred pain from the hip to the medial knee.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Hilton's law states that one nerve supplies the joint, the muscles moving it, and the skin over their insertion. The obturator nerve supplies the hip joint, adductors, and medial knee skin — so hip disease refers pain to the medial knee."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Excellent! This is why the clinical rule states: unexplained knee pain in a child → always image the hip. The obturator nerve connects all three targets per Hilton's law."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
